07656nam a22008655i 9780774827980DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748279807 a10.59962/97807748279802doi  a(DE-B1597)661383  a(OCoLC)884616461  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHM1136b.D457 2014 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a305.5/607222300aDemarginalizing Voices :bCommitment, Emotion, and Action in Qualitative Research /ced. by Sheryl C. Fabian, Maritza Felices-Luna, Jennifer M. Kilty. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAlternative Pathways: Opting for the Road Seldom Taken -- tObserving a Self-Chosen Death -- tEnsuring Aboriginal Women’s Voices Are Heard: Toward a Balanced Approach in Community-Based Research -- tCommitment and Participation: A Collective Action to Defend the Rights of Homeless People against Anti-Disorder Policing Practices in Montreal -- tDance in Prison: Narratives of the Body, Performativity, Methodology, and Criminology -- tProducing Feminist Knowledge: Lessons from the Past -- tThe Evolution of Feminist Research in the Criminological Enterprise: The Canadian Experience -- tEthical Quagmires: Regulating Qualitative Research -- tThe Politics of Threats in Correctional and Forensic Settings: The Specificities of Nursing Research -- tHow Positivism Is Colonizing Qualitative Research through Ethics Review -- tFighting the Big Bad Wolf: Why All the Fuss about Ethics Review Boards? -- tDoublespeak and Double Standards: Holding a Rogue University Administration to Account -- tEmotion Work and Identity: Self-Examination and Self-Awareness -- tReconciling the Irreconcilable: Resolving Emotionality and Research Responsibility When Working for the Traumatizer -- tGrappling with Reflexivity and the Role of Emotion in Criminological Analysis -- tEpistemological Violence, Psychological Whips, and Other Moments of Angst: Reflections on PhD Research -- tActivist Academic Whore: Negotiating the Fractured Otherness Abyss -- tConcluding Thoughts -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNumerous books explore the "how to" of qualitative research, but few discuss what it means to actually engage in it, particularly when researchers adopt alternative methods to shed light on the experiences of marginalized populations. In Demarginalizing Voices, scholars share personal stories about their research with marginalized populations, including Aboriginal peoples, sex workers, the dead and the dying, women and men in prison, women and men released from prison, and the homeless and the hospitalized. In the process, they answer questions of relevance to anyone engaged in qualitative research: What can scholars expect when their research requires them to establish human connections and relationships with their subjects? What role do ethics review boards and institutions play when researchers explore new, often less accepted methods? How do researchers reconcile academic life and its expectations with their activism? These powerful accounts from the cutting-edge of qualitative research not only create a space in academia that centres marginalized voices, they open up the field to new debates and discussion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMarginality, SocialxResearchxMethodology. 0aQualitative researchxMethodology. 0aSocial groupsxResearchxMethodology. 0aSocial sciencesxResearchxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aBellot, Céline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/